Pleiades Change Log: 2021-02-01 - 2021-02-31

New Place Resources

  • Block L7
    City block of Dura-Europos labeled according to modern excavators' scheme. The city's grid plan was established c. 150BCE and the site went out of use in 256 CE.
    Creators: Anne Chen
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker, Tom Elliott
  • Civita Giuliana
    The Civita Giuliana is located in the northern suburbium of Pompeii, about 700 meters from the city walls. Thus far the site has produced archaeological evidence of suburban villas in Pompeii's hinterland. Early twentieth-century excavations were carried out here, only to be published in 1994. Clandestine looting at the site brought about a cooperative effort to resume excavations in the interests of heritage protection in 2017.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors:
  • Clots de Raynaud
    Site of a Roman pottery workshop near the modern town of Sallèles-d'Aude, in use from the 1st century BCE-3rd century CE. The site is now a museum, the Musée des Potiers Gallo-Romains.
    Creators: Gabriel McKee
    Contributors:
  • Eandasaya
    The temple of the goddess Ištar of the Star, Eandasaya (“House Which Rivals Heaven”), was located in the New City district of Babylon, in the eastern half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of two temples in that part of Babylon.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors:
  • Edikukalama
    The temple of the god Šamaš, Edikukalama (“House of the Judge of the Land”), was located in the Kumar district of Babylon, in the western half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of seven temples in that part of Babylon. Edikukalama is attested in the Old Babylonian Period and it was rebuilt in the Neo-Babylonian Period by Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 604–562 BC).
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors:
  • Edurkuga
    The dais of the Igīgū gods, Edurkuga (“House, Pure Abode”), was located in the TE.E (read as either Tê or Kisīri) district of Babylon, in the eastern half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of two daises in that part of Babylon.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors:
  • Eʾesirkalama
    The temple of the god Pisangunuk, Eʾesirkalama (“House of the Street of the Land”), was located in the Kumar district of Babylon, in the western half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of seven temples in that part of Babylon.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors:
  • Eʾešmah
    The temple of the god Ea, Eʾešmah (“Exalted House”), was located in the Kumar district of Babylon, in the western half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of seven temples in that part of Babylon.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker
  • Ekadima
    The temple of the god Belili, Ekadima (“House Which Creates ...”), was located in the Kumar district of Babylon, in the western half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of seven temples in that part of Babylon.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors:
  • Ekagula
    The dais of the Anunnakū gods, Ekagula (“House, Big Gate”), was located in the TE.E (read as either Tê or Kisīri) district of Babylon, in the eastern half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of two daises in that part of Babylon.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors:
  • Ekišnugal
    The temple of the god Sîn, Ekišnugal (“House of the Great Light”), was located in the Kullab district of Babylon, in the eastern half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of four temples in that part of Babylon. The temple is mentioned in Old Babylonian Period texts and was (re)built by the Old Babylonian king Abī-ēšuh (r. ca. 1711–1684 BC) and the Neo-Babylonian ruler Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 604–562 BC). The temple survived into the Hellenistic Period.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors:
  • Ekitušgirzal
    The temple of the goddess Bēlet-Eanna, Ekitušgirzal (“House, Abode of Joy”), was located in the New City district of Babylon, in the eastern half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of two temples in that part of Babylon.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors:
  • Emekiliburur
    The temple of the goddess Šarrat-Larsa, Emekiliburur (“House which Gathers All the Me’s”), was located in the Kullab district of Babylon, in the eastern half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of four temples in that part of Babylon.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors:
  • Emesikila
    The temple of the god Amurru, Emesikila (“House of Pure Me’s”), was located in the Kumar district of Babylon, in the western half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of seven temples in that part of Babylon. Emesikila is mentioned in Old Babylonian sources.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors:
  • Emeurur
    The temple of the goddess Nanāya, Emeurur (“House which Gathers the Me’s”), was located in the TE.E (read as either Tê or Kisīri) district of Babylon, in the eastern half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was the only temple in that part of Babylon.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors:
  • Enamhe
    The temple of the god Adad, Enamhe (“House of Plenty”), was located in the Kumar district of Babylon, in the western half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of seven temples in that part of Babylon. Enamhe was (re)built by the the Old Babylonian kings Sūmû-lā-El (r. ca. 1881–1845 BC) and Hammu-rāpi (r. ca. 1792–1750 BC) and the Neo-Babylonian ruler Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 604–562 BC).
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker
  • Enamtila
    The temple of the god Bēl-mātāti (Enlil), Enamtila (“House of Life”), was located in the Kumar district of Babylon, in the western half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of seven temples in that part of Babylon. Enamtila is mentioned in Old Babylonian and Kassite Period texts.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors:
  • Esag
    The temple of the god Lugalbanda, Esag (“Foremost House”), was located in the Kullab district of Babylon, in the eastern half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of four temples in that part of Babylon.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors:
  • Eurguba
    The temple of the god Pisangunuk, Eurguba (“House, Established Foundation”), was located in the Kullab district of Babylon, in the eastern half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was one of four temples in that part of Babylon.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors:
  • Eurunanam
    The temple of the god Nabû, Eurunanam (“House, the Very City”), was located in the New City district of Babylon, in the eastern half of the inner city. According to the Babylonian topographical text Tintir = Babylon Tablet IV, it was the only dais in that part of Babylon.
    Creators: Jamie Novotny
    Contributors:
  • HaBesor Stream
    The largest stream of the southern Negev, the HaBesor Stream (Hebrew: נחל הבשור‎, Nahal HaBesor) is a wadi that flows from Mount Boker into the Mediterranean Sea near Al-Zahra in the Gaza Strip, where it is known as the Wadi Ghazzeh.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors:
  • House of Dionysos at Paphos
    Roman villa at Nea Paphos on Cyprus containing extensive mosaic floors.
    Creators: Gabriel McKee
    Contributors:
  • Ketef Hinnom
    Cave tomb complex located southwest of Jerusalem containing burials dated to the 6th century BCE.
    Creators: Gabriel McKee
    Contributors:
  • Synagogue phase 2
    Renovation of the synagogue at Dura-Europos c. 244 CE. The date for the renovation and expansion of the Synagogue (phase 2) is based on aramaic inscriptions painted on decorative ceiling tiles from the building's assembly hall.
    Creators: Anne Chen
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker, Tom Elliott
  • Tell Afis
    Iron Age settlement in Syria. The site has been tentatively identified as Hadarikka/Hazrek, the capital of the region of Luhuti/Luash, which became part of the kingdom of Hamath around 796 BCE.
    Creators: Gabriel McKee
    Contributors:
  • Tell Ras Budran
    An unusual circular "fort" dating to the Old Kingdom period of ancient Egypt.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors:
  • Temple of Zeus Trossou
    An epigraphically attested temple at or near ancient Atyochorion (modern Akkent in Turkey).
    Creators: Noah Kaye, Tom Elliott
    Contributors:
  • Vižula Maritime Villa
    An extensive maritime villa of the Roman period occupied the western and southern coasts of the Vižula peninsula, located near modern Medulin in Croatia.
    Creators: Francis Tassaux
    Contributors: Tom Elliott

  • Agoranis (river)
    Arrian (quoting Megasthenes) lists the Agoranis among a large number of tributaries of the Ganges river. Some modern scholarship (e.g., Tomaschek in RE) has therefore identified it with the modern Gogra (Ghaghara); however, Erdosy in BAtlas silently rejects this view, preferring to identify it as a distributary of the Ganges, the modern Garai (Gorai) in Bangladesh.
    Creators: M.U. Erdosy
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
    Modifications: location from osm created by products.pleiadesentity.browser.osm.osmlocationfactory
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker

  • Amphitheater of Dura-Europos
    Intramural amphitheater located within the military sector on the north side of Dura-Europos. Built on the site of the former Bath F3, which was destroyed by fire. The amphitheater's dedication in 216 CE is attested by an inscription found fallen from above entrance C on the south side of the amphitheater.

  • Bottino
    A lead and silver vein deposit in Italy's Apuane Alps region, mined most extensively in the 16th and 19th centuries of the modern era. Scholars have long accepted a history of exploitation here going back to the Etruscan period. Metallurgical analysis of artifacts from the late Villanovan settlement at Veii may indicate early iron extraction in this vicinity as well (Saviano 2006).
    Creators: W.V. Harris
    Contributors: DARMC, R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
    Modifications: added lead and iron tags; added multiple references; baseline created; darmc 19367 as related; location from osm created by products.pleiadesentity.browser.osm.osmlocationfactory; wrote summary
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker, Tom Elliott
  • Boubastis
    Boubastis (also known, in Arabic, as Tell Basta or, in Egyptian, as Per-Bast) was an ancient city in Egypt. It was located in the Nile Delta and served as the capital of the Am-Khent nome (the Bubastite nome), which was the 18th nome of Lower Egypt. It has been identified with the Biblical Pi-Beseth.
    Creators: A. Bernand
    Contributors: Brady Kiesling, Sean Gillies, Johan Åhlfeldt, Jeffrey Becker, Tom Elliott, DARMC, R. Talbert, Ryan M. Horne
    Modifications: cleanup
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker

    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors:
    Modifications: added wikidata
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker
  • Casa della statuetta indiana
    The so-called "Casa della statuetta indiana" (I.8.5) lies on the Via dell'Abbondanza. Excavated between 1930 and 1935, it was named for the fine ivory statuette (thought by some to depict Lakshmi) found inside. The house has a slightly irregular floor plan with some rooms added to the structure from adjacent properties.
    Creators: Holly Sypniewski
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker, Gabriel Moss, Tom Elliott
    Modifications: added arachne ref.
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker
  • Casa del pomarius Felix
    This house (I.8.2) opens onto the Via dell'Abbondanza and is connected to the taberna at I.8.1 and the shop at I.8.3. It was named the "Casa del pomarius Felix" from electoral programmata painted on its facade. It has a typical atrium-peristyle plan.
    Creators: Valeria Vitale, Rebecca Benefiel
    Contributors: Jeffrey Becker

  • Klaudianon
    A Roman and Late-antique fort and quarry at Mons Claudianus (modern Jabal Faţīrah) and in the associated Deir Wadi Umm Hussein in Egypt's eastern desert. It is often referred to in scholarly literature and the press simply as "Mons Claudianus" because of its location. Excavations at the site are notable in part for the recovery of a large textual archive that details the operations and daily life of soldiers and workers at the site.
    Creators: S.E. Sidebotham
    Contributors: DARMC, R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
    Modifications: cleanup references; ctype
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker

  • La Cheppe
    A Roman camp referred to as the "Camp of Attila", a site that some associate with the Battle of the Catalaunian Plains that occurred on June 20 of A.D. 451.
    Creators: C. Haselgrove, J. Kunow
    Contributors: DARMC, R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Johan Åhlfeldt, Jeffrey Becker, Tom Elliott

  • Laci(ni)murga
    Following TIR, the Barrington Atlas tentatively placed this ancient settlement at the archaeological site in Spain known today as Cerro del Cogolludo, which is located near the modern town of Navalvillar de Pela. Variants of the ancient placename are attested in inscriptions and in Ptolemy and Pliny. The latter two differ in provincial association, leading some scholars to speculate that two separate settlements with similar names existed in ancient times.
    Creators: Jr., F.H. Stanley, R.C. Knapp
    Contributors: DARMC, R. Talbert, R. Warner, Jeffrey Becker, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott
    Modifications: added cordero ruiz 2010; added darmc reference to maintain linkage after retracting less precise location; added epigraphically attested ethnic name; cleaned up other references; edited; initial revision; summary; updated old cil reference to hep online
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker, Tom Elliott

  • Lago dell’Accesa (archaeological site)
    The archaeological site of Lago dell’Accesa, in the locality known as "La Pesta", is situated nearby the lake of Lago dell'Accesa. The site was situated so as to exploit local mineral resources and the archaeological remains provide extensive evidence for habitation from the ninth through sixth centuries B.C.
    Creators: W.V. Harris

  • Le Ciliegeta
    The site of Le Ciliegeta, near the source of the river Arno, served as a rich stips votiva. The site was discovered in 1836. The finds included over 600 bronzes, more than 1,000 pieces of aes rude, 2,000 weapons, and other artifacts.
    Creators: W.V. Harris
    Contributors: DARMC, R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Jeffrey Becker, Elizabeth Robinson, Tom Elliott
    Modifications: wikipedia
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker

  • Parentium
    Ancient Parentium, now Poreč, Croatia, was a city on the western coast of the Istrian peninsula. There is archaeological evidence of Illyrian settlement from the Bronze Age onward. The site factors in Roman campaigns of the second century BC. The settlement became an oppidum civium Romanorum and then was advanced to municipium by Augustus. Tiberius dubbed it Colonia Iulia Parentium in the first century AD.
    Creators: M. Šašel Kos, P. Kos
    Contributors: Sean Gillies, Johan Åhlfeldt, Jeffrey Becker, Tom Elliott, DARMC, Nathalie Prévôt, R. Talbert, Francis Tassaux
    Modifications: parentium has never been a castrum in the second century bc (francis tassaux); updates contributor provides no evidence to support claim - entries in pecs, np, elsewhere support the id.
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker

  • Temple A
    So-called "Temple A" is a structure of the third century B.C. and is likely the Temple of Juturna that was vowed by Caius Lutatius Catulus following his victory against the Carthaginians in 241 B.C. It was later converted into a church, the apse of which remains visible.
    Creators: Jeffrey Becker
    Contributors: Brady Kiesling
    Modifications: added vici.org 39261: largo di torre argentina, temple a
    Actors: Jeffrey Becker

  • Unnamed quarries to the west of Thiounta
    Waelkens 1987 describes the discovery of a quarry district referred to as Taşlı Göl. It is to be located between the villages of Doğanlı, Gözler, and Çindere. This site is approximately 25 km northwest of Pamukkale. The marble from these quarries is identified as Thiounta marble on the basis of comparison with the coarser marble of Hierapolis.
    Creators: T. Drew Bear
    Contributors: R. Talbert, Sean Gillies, Tom Elliott, Jeffrey Becker
    Modifications: added tags; cnxn; consulted waelkens 1987 which is vague on locations. updated title and summary on that basis. place type = quarry; update waelkens 1987
